Technically the integral calc teachers tell u of 1/x is a straight up lie actually
when they say “f(x) + c” for some function f(x), they’re implicitly tryna mean the set of all functions that look like that form

But for 1/x (outside of x = 0), the anti derivative they tell u of ln(|x|) + c is the piece wise function 

ln(x) + c for x > 0 
ln(-x) + c for x < 0

In reality this does not capture the form of the full set of functions that’s derivatives r 1/x, instead you’d want any function of the form:

ln(x) + c for x > 0 
ln(-x) + d for x < 0
